FairPrice

AI Consumer Pricing Shield

Mission:
Prevent hidden price discrimination by using AI to detect, neutralize, and expose personalized pricing based on consumer data.

Core principle:

The same product should cost the same amount regardless of income, device, browsing history, or inferred wealth.

⸻

Problem

Modern pricing systems increasingly use behavioral and personal data to adjust prices.

Examples of signals used by pricing engines:
	•	ZIP code / neighborhood wealth
	•	device type (iPhone vs Android)
	•	browsing history
	•	urgency signals
	•	purchase history
	•	loyalty profile
	•	time-on-page
	•	travel behavior
	•	credit indicators
	•	cookies and cross-site trackers

Result:

Two people buying the same item at the same moment may see different prices.

This is often called:

surveillance pricing or algorithmic price discrimination

Consumers rarely know it is happening.

⸻

Solution

FairPrice acts as a pricing firewall between consumers and sellers.

It uses AI and multi-session testing to determine whether a seller is changing prices based on personal signals.

If so, it:
	1.	detects the discrimination
	2.	attempts to bypass it
	3.	documents evidence

⸻

Core Features

1. Price Neutralization Mode

The app creates a neutral consumer profile when shopping.

Signals are normalized:
	•	generic browser fingerprint
	•	neutral location precision
	•	tracker blocking
	•	session reset
	•	guest checkout preference

Goal:

Force the seller to show a baseline price.

⸻

2. Multi-Profile Price Testing

When a product page loads, the system runs parallel checks.

Example profiles:
	•	logged-in user
	•	logged-out user
	•	iPhone device
	•	desktop device
	•	neutral location
	•	high-income ZIP proxy
	•	first-time visitor

The AI compares prices across profiles.

⸻

3. Fairness Score

Each seller receives a pricing fairness rating.

Example:

Green
Consistent pricing

Yellow
Moderate variation detected

Red
High probability of personalized pricing

⸻

4. Auto Price Recovery

If a higher price is detected the app attempts:
	•	clean-room reload
	•	guest checkout
	•	cookie reset
	•	profile switch
	•	neutral routing

The goal is to automatically obtain the lowest neutral price.

⸻

5. Evidence Ledger

FairPrice stores verifiable evidence:
	•	timestamp
	•	product
	•	price variations
	•	test conditions
	•	screenshots or hashes

Users can export reports for:
	•	regulators
	•	journalists
	•	class actions
	•	consumer protection agencies

